# Unity 6.3 LTS - C# Conventions & Ecosystem

## Engine & Stack
- **Unity 6000.3.6f1** (Unity 6.3 LTS), URP 17.3.0, C# 9 (`LangVersion 9.0`), `netstandard2.1`
- **Input stack is mixed**:
  - Primary gameplay intents are read via `UnityEngine.InputSystem.InputAction` (`PlayerInputBridge`)
  - Legacy key polling still exists in some UI/gameplay scripts via `UnityEngine.Input`
  - Do not introduce a third input abstraction unless explicitly requested
- **TextMeshPro** is part of `com.unity.ugui` 2.0.0 — use `TMPro.TMP_Text` / `TMPro.TextMeshProUGUI`
- **Single scene** — no `DontDestroyOnLoad`, no additive loading, no scene transitions
- **Solution**: `who-wired-this.sln` → `Assembly-CSharp.csproj` + `Assembly-CSharp-Editor.csproj`

## Namespace Convention
Gameplay scripts should live under `WhoWiredThis.*`:
```
WhoWiredThis.Core          → GameManager, ScoreManager, TimerManager
WhoWiredThis.Player        → PlayerInputBridge, PlayerActions
WhoWiredThis.Interactables → IInteractable, Collectible, ClueInteractable, PuzzleSocket, TestButton
WhoWiredThis.Inventory     → InventoryManager
WhoWiredThis.UI            → HUDController, InventoryUI, InventorySlotUI, MessagePanel
WhoWiredThis.Environment   → ZoneTrigger
WhoWiredThis.Data          → ItemData (ScriptableObject)
```
- If touching legacy scripts without a namespace (for example utility/test scripts), prefer keeping edits minimal unless the task is explicitly a cleanup/refactor.

## Unity Lifecycle Order
```
Awake → OnEnable → Start → Update / FixedUpdate / LateUpdate → OnDisable → OnDestroy
```
- Use `Awake` for self-initialisation and singleton registration
- Use `Start` for cross-component references (other singletons are ready)
- Use `LateUpdate` for camera follow

## Serialization Rules
- `[SerializeField] private` — prefer over `public` for Inspector-exposed fields
- `[Header("...")]` to group related Inspector fields
- `[Tooltip("...")]` on public/serialized fields when intent is non-obvious
- ScriptableObjects use `[CreateAssetMenu]`
- In new gameplay code, avoid adding new public mutable fields unless there is a clear external API need
- Connect scene objects/components to code through serialized inspector properties whenever possible

## Singleton Pattern (this project)
```csharp
public static MyManager Instance { get; private set; }
void Awake()
{
    if (Instance != null && Instance != this) { Destroy(gameObject); return; }
    Instance = this;
}
```

## Component Access
- Cache `GetComponent<T>()` in `Awake`, never in `Update`
- Use `CompareTag("Player")` not `tag == "Player"`
- Prefer `TryGetComponent<T>(out T c)` over null-checked `GetComponent`

## Unity C# Specifics
- `MonoBehaviour` cannot use constructors — use `Awake`/`Start`
- `Vector3`, `Quaternion`, `Color` are value types (structs)
- `Mathf` for math (not `System.Math`)
- `Time.deltaTime` for frame-rate-independent motion
- `Physics.OverlapSphere` / `Raycast` for spatial queries
- `Renderer.material` creates an instance; use `sharedMaterial` when not modifying per-instance

## Events & Callbacks
Use `System.Action` / `System.Action<T>` for lightweight events.
- Subscribe in `Start`/`OnEnable`
- Unsubscribe in `OnDestroy`/`OnDisable` to avoid stale listeners on scene reload or object recreation

## URP Materials
- Use `UnityEngine.Rendering.Universal` namespace for URP-specific APIs
- Lit Shader properties: `_BaseColor`, `_BaseMap`, `_Metallic`, `_Smoothness`
- Set material color at runtime: `renderer.material.SetColor("_BaseColor", color)`

## Common Pitfalls to Avoid
- Never call `FindObjectOfType` in `Update` — cache in `Awake`/`Start`
- Don't use `GameObject.Find` — wire references via Inspector or singleton
- `Destroy(gameObject)` is deferred to end of frame; set active false if immediate hide is needed
- `Physics.Raycast` uses world-space origin; local-to-world transform when needed
- Before assuming singleton instances exist, null-check where reasonable (`Instance?....`) to avoid race/missing-reference errors
- Prefer scene-authored objects and prefabs over runtime creation when objects are gameplay-meaningful and repeatable
